###############################################################################
Provide a detailed description of your project and scope
###############################################################################
  A project suggestion was to 'Create software or game to teach people about a 
  computer security topic'. We decided to create a CTF competition so that
  people beginning to do CTF could have a good resource for practice and
  familiarization with the format. This was also done as practice for ourselves
  in gaining familiarity with CTF competitions. We covered several topics that
  require a variety of tools and skills.

  We used the CTFd framework to set up our CTF and included four challenges:
    "the journey begins" - a buffer overflow challenge (created by Ryan)
    "gandalf's research" - a packet capture forensics challenge (created by Bryan)
    "sql challenge" - a medley of SQL injection problems (created by Bryan)
    "an old map" - a multi-part challenge involving steganography and several
      cryptography steps (created by Julian)
  
  We looked at previous CTF events (cited below) for inspiration and for help
  in learning how to write these types of challenges. We also wrote writeups
  for each challenge explaining how to solve them.
  
  Our CTF challenge loosely follows the plot of The Hobbit by J.R.R. Tolkien
  to make it more enjoyable and cohesive.
  
###############################################################################
Project progress/status
###############################################################################
We set up our CTFd site and hosted all necessary content on the server so that
the challenges are accessible to participants. We completed writeups for every
challenge and added them to the Github for referencing.

###############################################################################
Marked timeline/project plan/chart
###############################################################################
Completed:
  Determine framework and research how to create a CTF challenge. (3/30)
  CTF overview meeting to discuss range/difficulty/number of questions. (4/01)
  Setting up CTFd platform. (4/04)
  Challenge research. (4/05-4/13)
  Completing writeups for all problems. (4/11-4/13)
  Finishing touches. (4/13-4/14)
  Submit. (4/14)
    
###############################################################################
Reasoning for any changes to project plan (additions/subtractions/substitutions)
and how that did or did not change project scope
###############################################################################
We scaled back the variety of challenge difficulties due to the difficulty in
implementing and solving higher-level challenges. We rearranged certain tasks
while completing the project (specifically, we set up the server and CTFd
platform early so that we could test certain things on it and familiarize
ourselves with it). We decided to not release the challenge to the class.

###############################################################################
Discussion of teamwork (who did what, how did you function as a team, etc)
###############################################################################
Each team member wrote 1-2 challenges for the CTF and the accompanying writeup(s),
as noted above. The team communicated over email, Google Hangouts, and through
Github Issues. Bryan set up the server for us and moved challenges onto it.

###############################################################################
User manual/instructions/directions (written for your project audience)
###############################################################################
The CTF challenge is accessible at http://34.66.235.224:8000. All needed
directions for participants are included on the site. Writeups for each
challenge are publicly accessible at https://github.com/JmanJr/security-4.

###############################################################################
Other information from proposal
###############################################################################
  Decide how you plan to “share” project files/resources/etc:
    We plan to collaborate using github. A challenge and its associated writeup
    be available on a public repository.

  Decide how you will communicate during the project:
    Email is will be the primary means of communication. However, we will also
    utilize githubs 'issues' tracker to manage project tasks and issues.

  Decide when you will be meeting as a team:
    We will have the general overview meeting once on (4/1) to discuss scope
    and types of challenges, but afterwards will only have brief progress check 
    meetings before every class period (~30 minutes) as a supplement to the 
    github issues tracker or email conversations.
    
  Decide penalties if group members miss deadlines, meetings, etc (point 
      deduction, donuts, pizza, extra work, etc):
    After class, the late person will buy item(s) from the upstairs GDC cafe up
    to a value of 10 USD per member of the group.
  
    If the person fails to show up for class, this punishment is carried over.

